Preheat the oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a #large pot{} of salted water for the potatoes.

Peel and chop the @potatoes{3} into 2cm chunks.

Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook until fork tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain the potatoes in a #colander{} and return to the #pot{}, off the heat.

Add a knob of @butter{knob} and a splash of @?milk{} or @?water{}. Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Cover to keep warm.

Trim the @carrot{2} then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Chop into roughly 1cm wide, 5cm long batons.

Pop the carrot onto a #large baking tray{}(lined).

Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

Roast on the top shelf until tender, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Pop the @breadcrumbs{1%pack} into a #bowl{}.

Cut the @Greek Style Cheese{100%g} into 2cm cubes.

In another bowl, mix 1 tbsp @water{1%tbsp} with 1 tsp @flour{1%tsp} (double both for 4p).

Toss the cheese cubes through the flour and water mixture and then carefully toss in the breadcrumbs.

Place a pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}. Fry the cheese cubes for ~{5-7%minutes}. Turn occasionally until golden on all sides. Remove from the pan and cover to keep warm.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Season the @21 Day Aged Irish Sirloin Steak{250%g} with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Return the pan to high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Fry the sirloin until browned, ~{1-2%minutes} each side for medium-rare.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging.

Pop in the garlic, @Balsamic Glaze{1%sachet} and a knob of @butter{knob}.

Once butter is melted use a #spoon{} to glaze the steaks.

Cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you'd like them more well-done.

Once cooked, transfer to a #board{}, cover and allow to rest, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Once rested, thinly slice.

Divide the @Baby Spinach{60%g} between #plates{} and top with the sliced steak.

Serve the velvety mash, fried cheese and tender carrots alongside.

Drizzle any remaining sauce from the pan over the sliced steak.